{{For|John Lalor (1814–1856), Irish journalist and author|John Lalor}}
{{Infobox writer <!-- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_person for complete template. Note: Wikipedia supports a variety of different Infobox templates, and a more specific template may be appropriate for this person (for example, {{Infobox writer}}). --> | name = John Joseph Lalor | image = | size = <!-- Default 200px --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth based on age as of date|58|1899|6|9|noage=1}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and given age|1899|06|09|58}}<ref name="EveningStar18990610">{{cite news |title=Dies from Shock. Unexpected Termination of John J. Lalor's Injuries. |page=8 |publisher=The Evening Star (Washington, D. C.) |date=June 10, 1899 |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1899-06-10/ed-1/seq-8/ |accessdate=2014-07-09}}</ref> | death_place = Washington, D. C. | nationality = | other_names = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = | known_for = | notable_works = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = }}
'''John Joseph Lalor''' ({{Birth based on age as of date|58|1899|6|9|noage=1}} to 9 June 1899<ref name="EveningStar18990610"/>) political scientist. Translator of work by [[Ludwig Nohl]] and [[Wilhelm Roscher]] and best known for ''[[Cyclopaedia of Political Science, Political Economy, and the Political History of the United States]]'' (1895).
<!-- Washington Law Reporter shows a John J. Lalor deceased in District of Columbia in 1899 [https://books.google.com/books?id=CtkZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA618 page 618] -->
==Biography==
In 1885, Lalor taught at East Side High School, Milwaukee.<ref name="EveningStarFuneralNotice">{{cite news |title=Funeral of John J. Lalor. Services at St. Matthew's Church This Morning |page=8 |publisher=The Evening Star |location=Washington, D. C. |date=June 12, 1899 |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1899-06-12/ed-1/seq-8/ |accessdate=2014-07-12}}</ref> Lalor worked as a translator in the Director of Mint, U. S. Treasury Department.<ref>{{cite news |title=The News in Brief |publisher=Republican news item |date=June 15, 1899 |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86081854/1899-06-15/ed-1/seq-8/ |location=Laport, Pa.}}</ref> Lalor collaborated with [[Louis Wolowski]], Ludwig Nohl, and [[Paul Shorey]]. He translated works by [[Rudolf von Jhering]] and Wilhelm Roscher. He translated from German two works by Ludwig Nohl, a biography of [[Ludwig Beethoven]] in ''Life of Beethoven'' (1881)<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofbeethoven00nohl_0 |title=Life of Beethoven |last=Nohl |first=Ludwig |authorlink=Ludwig Nohl |translator=John Joseph Lalor |year=1881}}</ref> and [[Wolfgang Mozart]] in ''Life of Mozart'' (1880).<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924018010466 |title=Life of Mozart |last=Nohl |first=Ludwig |authorlink=Ludwig Nohl |translator=John Joseph Lalor |year=1880}}</ref>
In 1899, Lalor died from injuries due to a fall.<ref name="EveningStarFuneralNotice"/>
