{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}
'''Sir Martin Wyatt Holdgate''' [[Companion of the Bath|CB]] (born 14 January 1931 in [[Horsham]], [[England]]) is an English [[biologist]] and environmental scientist.

==Early life==
Holdgate was born in Horsham, England on 14 January 1931, grew up in [[Blackpool]],<ref name="FLD">{{cite web|url=http://www.fld.org.uk/sir-martin-holdgate-new-president-of-friends-of-the-lake-district.html|title=Sir Martin Holdgate – New President of Friends of the Lake District|date=22 July 2014|publisher=Friends of the Lake District|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> and was educated at [[Arnold School]]. He then attended [[Cambridge University]] as an undergraduate at [[Queens' College|Queens' College, Cambridge]] from 1949, graduating in 1952 with degrees in [[zoology]] and [[botany]]<ref>[http://www.quns.cam.ac.uk/queens/misc/Eminent.html Eminent Alumni] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090616042915/http://www.quns.cam.ac.uk/Queens/Misc/Eminent.html |date=16 June 2009 }}, Queens's College, Cambridge, accessed 16 February 2010</ref> and, subsequently, a doctorate in insect physiology.<ref name="FLD" />

== Career ==

He taught at [[Manchester University]], [[Durham University]] and Cambridge, as well as undertaking expeditions to [[Tristan da Cunha]], south-west [[Chile]] and the [[Antarctic]].<ref name="FLD" /> He was Chief Biologist to the [[British Antarctic Survey]], then research director of the [[Nature Conservancy Council]] and, for eighteen years, Chief Scientist and head of research at the [[Department of the Environment]].<ref name="FLD" /> Subsequently, he was Director General of the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref name="FLD" />

After his formal retirement, he was a member of the [[Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution]] and served as co-chair of the Intergovernmental Panel on Forests, and Secretary of the [[UN Secretary General]]'s High-Level Board on Sustainable Development.<ref name="FLD" />

